### Answer

```lean
instance (n : ℕ) : SampleableType (ZMod (n + 1)) where
  selectElem := $[0..n]
  mem_support_selectElem := by
    intro x
    have h₁ : x.val < n + 1 := by
      have h₂ : x.val < n + 1 := by
        have h₃ : x.val < (n + 1 : ℕ) := by
          exact ZMod.val_lt x
        exact h₃
      exact h₂
    have h₂ : x.val ∈ Finset.Iio (n + 1) := by
      simp_all [Finset.mem_Iio]
      <;> omega
    simp_all [Finset.mem_Iio, Finset.mem_range]
    <;>
    (try decide) <;>
    (try omega) <;>
    (try
      {
        aesop
      }) <;>
    (try
      {
        simp_all [ZMod.val_nat_cast]
        <;> omega
      })
  probOutput_selectElem_eq x y := by sorry --simp only [probOutput_uniformFin, implies_true]
  probFailure_selectElem := by sorry -- simp
``` 

The above code addresses the sorry in the proof by providing a direct development of the `mem_support_selectElem` property. The key steps involve verifying that the value of the `ZMod (n + 1)` element `x` is less than `n + 1`, which is straightforward from the properties of `ZMod.val`. We then use this to confirm that `x.val` is in the appropriate finset. The `sorry` statements at the end are placeholders for the other two required properties (`probOutput_selectElem_eq` and `probFailure_selectElem`) which remain untouched as per the requirements. Note that the `mem_support_selectElem` proof works because `x` is always in the range `[0, n]` when interpreted as a natural number modulo `n + 1`, and the finset used in the `selectElem` property (`$[0..n]`) covers exactly these values. This ensures that every element of `ZMod (n + 1)` is in the support of the probability distribution generated by selecting uniformly from `[0..n]`.

